What is CABG?

Coronary Artery Bypass Grafting (CABG, "cabbage") surgically reroutes blood around blocked coronary arteries using harvested vessels.

Graft Sources:
â€¢ Saphenous vein (leg) - most common
â€¢ Internal mammary artery - best patency
â€¢ Radial artery (arm) - alternative
Animation Shows:
â€¢ Red particles = oxygenated blood
â€¢ Purple vessel = bypass graft
â€¢ Yellow mass = coronary blockage
â€¢ Pulsing heart = cardiac contraction
Post-CABG patients may have atypical chest pain from sternotomy. Always compare current ECG to post-op baselines. Expect Q waves and T-wave changes.

EMS Considerations

Ask: Number of grafts, surgery date, recent cath?

Meds: Antiplatelet, statins, beta-blockers

Risk: Elevated bleeding risk

2. Cardiac Cycle and Heart Sounds

Coordinated mechanical events of atrial and ventricular systole/diastole

S1-S2 Active
ðŸŽ¬ Beating Heart Animation
ðŸ“– Clinical Explanation

Cardiac Cycle Phases

1. Atrial Systole: Atria contract, pushing blood through AV valves. Provides "atrial kick" (~20% of filling).
2. Isovolumetric Contraction: Ventricles begin contracting. AV valves close â†’ S1 "Lub"
3. Ventricular Ejection: Semilunar valves open. Blood ejected into aorta/pulmonary artery.
4. Isovolumetric Relaxation: Ventricles relax. Semilunar valves close â†’ S2 "Dub"
5. Ventricular Filling: AV valves open, passive filling occurs.

Heart Sounds

S1: AV valve closure - best at apex

S2: Semilunar valve closure - best at base

S3 gallop = volume overload (CHF) "Ken-TUC-ky". S4 gallop = stiff ventricle (HTN) "TEN-nes-see"

ECG Waveform Components

P Wave (Orange/Yellow):
â€¢ Atrial depolarization from SA node
â€¢ Duration: <0.12 sec (3 boxes)
â€¢ Amplitude: <2.5mm
â€¢ Absent in A-fib, inverted in junctional
QRS Complex (Green/Purple):
â€¢ Ventricular depolarization
â€¢ Q = initial negative deflection
â€¢ R = first positive deflection
â€¢ S = negative after R
â€¢ Duration: <0.12 sec (3 boxes)
T Wave (Blue/Green):
â€¢ Ventricular repolarization
â€¢ Usually upright (except aVR)
â€¢ Inverted = ischemia
â€¢ Tall/peaked = hyperkalemia
ECG cannot detect SA node, AV node, Bundle of His, or Purkinje activity - these structures are too small.

Coronary Arteries

RCA (Right Coronary):
â€¢ Supplies: RA, RV, SA node (60%), AV node (90%), inferior LV
â€¢ ECG: II, III, aVF
â€¢ Occlusion â†’ Bradycardia, heart blocks
LAD (Left Anterior Descending):
â€¢ Supplies: Anterior LV, septum, apex
â€¢ ECG: V1-V4
â€¢ "Widow maker" - high mortality
LCx (Left Circumflex):
â€¢ Supplies: LA, lateral LV
â€¢ ECG: I, aVL, V5-V6
â€¢ Often "silent" - check V7-V9
Inferior STEMI with III > II suggests RCA. Always check V4R - RV infarction patients are preload-dependent. Avoid nitrates!

Dual Circulation

Pulmonary Circuit (Low Pressure):
1. Deoxy blood â†’ RA via vena cava
2. RA â†’ RV via tricuspid
3. RV â†’ Pulm artery (deoxy!)
4. Gas exchange in lungs
5. Pulm veins (oxy!) â†’ LA
Systemic Circuit (High Pressure):
1. Oxy blood â†’ LA from lungs
2. LA â†’ LV via mitral
3. LV â†’ Aorta
4. Oâ‚‚ delivered to tissues
5. Deoxy blood â†’ RA via vena cava
Pulmonary ARTERIES carry deoxy blood (blue), pulmonary VEINS carry oxy blood (red). Opposite of systemic!

Hemodynamics

Preload: Venous return

Afterload: Resistance (SVR)

CO = HR Ã— SV

Conduction Pathway

SA Node (Yellow):
â€¢ Location: RA near SVC
â€¢ Rate: 60-100 bpm (dominant)
â€¢ Creates P wave
AV Node (Orange):
â€¢ Location: Interatrial septum
â€¢ Rate: 40-60 bpm
â€¢ Delays impulse (PR interval)
Bundle Branches (Blue/Pink):
â€¢ RBB: Single fascicle
â€¢ LBB: Anterior & posterior
â€¢ BBB = wide QRS

â€¢ Rate: 20-40 bpm (escape)
â€¢ Rapid ventricular activation
Atropine works on SA/AV nodes. For infranodal blocks (wide escape), go straight to pacing!

Normal Sinus Rhythm

NSR Criteria:
â€¢ Rate: 60-100 bpm
â€¢ Regular R-R intervals
â€¢ P wave before every QRS

ST Segment Changes
